2026-04-16 12:15:56 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control Module 3 output cabling / terminals', 'Control Module 3 internal series path between its input and output on the 12 V line'] hypothesis_explanation='Voltage tracing with all switches ON and a good battery shows +12 V present at the PSU output and through Control Modules 1 and 2 (their outputs all measure +12 V on the designated positive conductor relative to PSU negative), but from Control Module output (+) 3 onward both conductors are at 0 V. This means that the 12 V line is being interrupted or shorted to 0 V at the transition between the output of Control Module 2 and the input/output of Control Module 3. Because all eight control modules were observed as having closed switches and no obvious LED‑circuit faults, the most plausible single fault is an open or incorrectly connected series path on the 12 V side at Control Module 3—either a defective internal series connection in CM3 or a mis‑terminated / faulty output terminal or cable at CM3. Repairing or replacing Control Module 3 (or its immediate output connection) should restore +12 V to the downstream modules and allow the lamp to operate when all switches are ON.'
